        "en": "The CDMO upcycle is expected to remain supportive over the medium term. Samsung Biologics is progressing toward its second bio-campus, targeting a production capacity exceeding 1.32 million liters by 2032, underpinned by sustained demand for biologics manufacturing. A wave of technology licensing deals in next-generation biomodalities—ADCs and bispecific antibodies—is building a visible milestone revenue pipeline for domestic platform companies such as ABL Bio and Alteogen. In the obesity and metabolic disease market, Hanmi's efpeglenatide and Peptron's long-acting GLP-1 formats are positioned to mark the inaugural year of domestically developed GLP-1 commercialization, while the global race among GLP-1 developers may also generate incremental CDMO demand. The structural expansion of AI-driven drug discovery and open-innovation partnerships with global big pharma represents a favorable backdrop for domestic biotech licensing activity. However, the persistent profitability bifurcation between top-tier CDMO/biosimilar firms and cash-burning KOSDAQ biotechs warrants close monitoring of individual clinical progression and burn rates."
