        "en": "The 2026–2027 period is expected to see a concentration of legislative reforms, including amendments to the Commercial Act and Capital Markets Act, mandatory treasury share cancellation, and the introduction of separate taxation on dividend income—developments that could structurally compress the chronic holding company discount. Mandatory treasury share cancellation, likely to take effect around June 2026, is expected to most directly benefit companies with high treasury share ratios: SK (24.8%), Doosan (17.9%), and LS (12.5%). POSCO Holdings has set a target for steel earnings to exceed 2024 levels in 2026, with ramp-up of new lithium facilities and completion of customer certifications for cathode materials serving as key re-rating catalysts. LS Group's focused investment in subsea cables and EV materials is gradually enhancing the realization potential of currently unlisted subsidiary values. The central medium-term question is whether expanding shareholder returns—driven by activist investors, growing minority shareholder influence, and strengthened board independence—can generate a virtuous cycle that meaningfully reduces the persistent NAV discount."
