        "en": "The 2026–2027 period is expected to represent the peak earnings realization phase for Korean shipbuilders, as high-value backlog orders convert into revenue. Clarkson Research projects LNG carrier orders to nearly double to 100 vessels in 2026 from 50 in 2025, driven by U.S. LNG export expansion, Qatar's fleet renewal demand, and the ongoing energy transition toward cleaner fuels. The Korea Chamber of Commerce and Industry forecasts 2026 shipbuilding exports to grow 8.6% year-on-year to approximately USD 33.9 billion, supported by LNG carrier and containership demand. The MASGA (Make American Shipbuilding Great Again) cooperation framework is materializing as a tangible growth driver: Hanwha Ocean operates Philly Shipyard and secured the first Korean naval MRO contract, while HD Hyundai Heavy Industries won a maintenance contract for USNS Alan Shepard, signaling a broadening of revenue streams into defense and services. With docks approaching full saturation, major yards retain strong pricing leverage to focus on high-margin segments such as LNG, ammonia, and dual-fuel carriers. Advancement in smart shipyard technology—including digital twins and process automation—and the commercialization of ammonia propulsion systems represent key long-term differentiators vis-à-vis Chinese competition."
